description.narrative:
Between 2008 and 2010, Sida and DfID supported a project to develop a regional development policy in Moldova (Improving the capacities of the the development of a policy for regional development). The project resulted in the establishment of the formal regulations and institutions needed to implement regional development policies. 
Regional institutions have been created in three broad development regions: North, Centre and South. Regional Development Councils (RDCs) with representatives of Local Public Authorities (LPAs), private sector and civil society awas established to act as decision making bodies at the regional level Tthey were created to assess, approve and monitor the Regional Development Strategies and related investment projects. At the implementation level, Regional Development Agencies (RDAs), were constituted as an administrative structure with executing functions, mainly related to investment project implementation.

This ongoing contribution focusses on the following areas:
• Improving the capacities of the Regional Development Agencies and of the Regional Development Councils in the areas regional planning and programming;
• Facilitating knowledge exchange between Local Public Authorities (LPAs) which are implementing innovative pilot projects for improving public services, and the regional institutions in order to foster dissemination/scaling up of best practices.

The lessons learned from the ongoing project on regional development were that the created institutions are still too weak to operate without support from donors. Within this context, and due to the increased demand for technical assistance, the Ministry of Regional Development and Construction (MRDC) and the Ministry of Economy (MoE, inter alias responsible for the EU-financed National Fund for Energy Efficiency) have approached the Swedish Embassy and GIZ, requesting the consideration of additional support to RDAs and LPAs for the following areas:
• To improve existing project concepts for investments in local public services and develop them to “ready-for-procurement” level;
• To increase the capacity to organize public procurements;
• To carry out quality control and site supervision of the implementation of investments;
• To strengthen management function such as project hand-over and registration.

The expected results follow the same logic as the previous project document prepared in 2011, but contain clearer formulated outcomes and outputs, which would allow for a more efficient follow-up on them. The additional Swedish funds are expected to contribute to:
• Improved capacities and credibility of RDAs;
• Increased transparency and better governance in management of public assets for regional development;
• Improved access of citizens to relevant local public services, inclusively through increased energy efficiency of public buildings.
